{
    "unitNumber": 21,
    "text": {
        "title": "Imperative",
        "sections": [
            {
                "title": "Use of the Imperative",
                "paragraphs": [
                    {
                        "id": 21.01,
                        "content": "The imperative is used, in Italian as in English, to express orders, commands, or strong requests:",
                        "table": {
                            "rows": [
                                ["**Guarda**!", "Look!"],
                                ["**Entrate**!", "Come in!"],
                                ["**Chiedi** a tuo padre.", "Ask your father."],
                                ["**Venga** domani, Signora!", "Come tomorrow, Madam!"],
                                ["**Andiamo**!", "Let’s go!"],
                                ["**Dammi** il libro.", "Give me the book."]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "content": "As well as orders and requests, the imperative can also be used to express wishes, invitations, encouragement, and advice:",
                        "table": {
                            "rows": [
                                ["**Passa** delle buone vacanze.", "Have a good holiday."],
                                ["**Ti ascolto**: **dimmi** tutto.", "I’m listening to you: tell me everything."],
                                ["**Non ti preoccupare**.", "Don’t worry."],
                                ["**Hai l’aria stanca**: **vai** a letto!", "You look tired: go to bed!"]
                            ]
                        }
                    }
                ]
            },
            {
                "title": "Forms of the Imperative",
                "paragraphs": [
                    {
                        "id": 21.02,
                        "content": "Regular verbs in **-are**, **-ere**, and **-ire** are conjugated as follows:",
                        "table": {
                            "headers": ["", "Parlare (To speak)", "Prendere (To take/get)", "Partire (To leave)"],
                            "rows": [
                                ["tu", "parla", "prendi", "parti"],
                                ["Lei", "parli", "prenda", "parta"],
                                ["noi", "parliamo", "prendiamo", "partiamo"],
                                ["voi", "parlate", "prendete", "partite"],
                                ["Loro", "parlino", "prendano", "partano"]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "content": "Some verbs ending in **-ire** add **-isc-**, as in the present indicative (see Unit 5):",
                        "table": {
                            "headers": ["Finire (To finish)", "Italian", "English"],
                            "rows": [
                                ["tu", "finisci", "finish"],
                                ["Lei", "finisca", "finish"],
                                ["noi", "finiamo", "let us finish"],
                                ["voi", "finite", "finish"],
                                ["Loro", "finiscano", "finish"]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "content": "In the first person plural, the meaning is more that of a suggestion than an order, made to a group of which we are part (cf. the English ‘Let’s have a coffee’). The third person singular and plural are only used for the polite form.",
                        "table":{
                            "rows":[
                                ["Parlate con i vostri insegnanti.", "Speak to your teachers."],
                                ["Prendi un analgesico.", "Take a painkiller."],
                                ["Partiamo subito.", "Let’s leave immediately."],
                                ["Finisci il compito!", "Finish your homework!"],
                                ["Prenda la prima (strada) a destra.", "Take the first (street) on the right."]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "id": 21.03,
                        "content": "Verbs ending in -care and -gare keep the hard sound of c and g by adding h before the endings of the third person singular (Lei) and the first and third persons plural (noi and Loro):",
                        "table":{
                            "headers":["Cercare", "Pagare"],
                            "rows":[
                                ["cerca","paga"],
                                ["cerchi","paghi"],
                                ["cerchiamo","paghiamo"],
                                ["cercate","pagate"],
                                ["cerchino","paghino"]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "content": "Examples:",
                        "table":{
                            "rows":[
                                ["Cerchiamo casa in questa zona!", "Let’s look for a flat in this area!"],
                                ["Paghi il conto, per favore, Signora.", "Pay the bill, please(, Madam)."]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "id": 21.04,
                        "content": "Verbs ending in -iare have only one -i in the second person singular and the first and third persons plural:",
                        "table":{
                            "headers":["Cominciare", "Mangiare"],
                            "rows":[
                                ["comincia", "mangia"],
                                ["cominci", "mangi"],
                                ["cominciamo", "mangiamo"],
                                ["cominciate", "mangiate"],
                                ["comincino", "mangino"]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "content": "Examples:",
                        "table":{
                            "rows":[
                                ["Cominci a lavorare, Signora!", "Start working(, Madam)"],
                                ["Muoio di fame: mangiamo qualcosa!", "I’m starving: let’s eat something!"]
                            ]
                        }
                    }
                ]
            },
            {
                "title": "Forms of some irregular verbs",
                "paragraphs": [
                    {
                        "id": 21.05,
                        "content": "Essere and avere are irregular in the imperative:",
                        "table":{
                            "headers":["Essere", "Avere"],
                            "rows":[
                                ["sii", "abbi"],
                                ["sia", "abbia"],
                                ["siamo", "abbiamo"],
                                ["siate", "abbiate"],
                                ["siano", "abbiano"]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "content": "Examples:",
                        "table":{
                            "rows":[
                                ["Siate gentili!", "Be kind!"],
                                ["Abbi pazienza!", "Be patient! [lit. have patience]"],
                                ["Sia pronta per le 10, Signora.", "Be ready by 10(, Madam)."]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "id": 21.06,
                        "content": "There are other verbs with irregular imperatives. Here are some of the most common:",
                        "table":{
                            "headers":["Dare", "Dire", "Fare"],
                            "rows":[
                                ["dai/da’*","di’","fai/fa’*"],
                                ["dia","dica","faccia"],
                                ["diamo","diciamo","facciamo"],
                                ["date","dite","fate"],
                                ["diano","dicano","facciano"]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "content": "",
                        "table":{
                            "headers":["Stare", "Andare", "Venire"],
                            "rows":[
                                ["stai/sta’*", "vai/va’*", "vieni"],
                                ["stia", "vada", "venga"],
                                ["stiamo", "andiamo", "veniamo"],
                                ["state", "andate", "venite"],
                                ["stiano", "vadano", "vengano"]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "content": "",
                        "table":{
                            "headers":["Sapere", "Uscire", "Bere"],
                            "rows":[
                                ["sappi", "esci", "bevi"],
                                ["sappia", "esca", "beva"],
                                ["sappiamo", "usciamo", "beviamo"],
                                ["sappiate", "uscite", "bevete"],
                                ["sappiano", "escano", "bevano"]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "content": "* The second person singular of these verbs has two forms: the form with the apostrophe is normally used with unstressed pronouns (see paragraph 10)",
                        "table":{
                            "rows":[
                                ["State attenti!", "Pay attention! [lit. be attentive]"], 
                                ["Fai/fa’ il compito!", "Do your homework!"], 
                                ["Vieni subito qui!", "Come here at once!"], 
                                ["Venga avanti, Signora!", "Come forward(, Madam)!"], 
                                ["Sappi che io non sono d’accordo.", "I want you to know that I don’t agree. [lit. know that I don’t agree]"], 
                                ["Di’ la verità.", "Tell the truth."]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "id": 21.07,
                        "content": "All verbs ending in -urre have the following pattern:",
                        "table":{
                            "headers":["", "Tradurre"],
                            "rows":[
                                ["-uci", "traduci"],
                                ["-uca", "traduca"],
                                ["-uciamo", "traduciamo"],
                                ["-ucete", "traducete"],
                                ["-ucano", "traducano"]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "content": "Examples:",
                        "table":{
                            "rows":[
                                ["Traduciamo insieme queste frasi.", "Let’s translate these sentences together."],
                                ["Traduca, per favore.", "Translate, please."]
                            ]
                        }
                    }
                ]
            },
            {
                "title": "Formal form",
                "paragraphs": 
                [
                    {
                        "id": 21.08,
                        "content": "We have already seen the forms used for the polite form. Care must be taken not to confuse imperative and present polite and familiar forms. Compare:",
                        "table":{
                            "headers":["", "", "Imperative", "Present"],
                            "rows":[
                                ["familiar", "(tu)", "parla", "parli"],
                                ["formal", "(Lei)", "parli", "parla"],
                                ["familiar", "(tu)", "leggi", "leggi"],
                                ["formal", "(Lei)", "legga", "legge"],
                                ["familiar", "(tu)", "esci/finisci", "esci/finisci"],
                                ["formal", "(Lei)", "esca/finisca", "esce/finisce"]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "content": "Examples:",
                        "table":{
                            "rows":[
                                ["Parla col direttore! [familiar imperative]", "Speak to the manager!"],
                                ["Parli col direttore, Signora. [formal imperative]", "Speak to the manager(, Madam)."],
                                ["Parli col direttore? [familiar present]", "Are you speaking to the manager?"],
                                ["Parla col direttore, Signora? [formal present]", "Are you speaking to the manager(, Madam)?"]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "content": "In the plural, as usual, the second person is more commonly used than the third:",
                        "table":{
                            "rows":[
                                ["Parlate col controllore.", "Speak to the conductor."],
                                ["(Parlino col controllore.)", "Speak to the conductor."],
                                ["Abbiate pazienza, Signori.", "Be patient, (ladies and) gentlemen."],
                                ["(Abbiano pazienza, Signori.)", "Be patient, (ladies and) gentlemen."]
                            ]
                        }
                    }
                ]
            },
            {
                "title": "Negative form",
                "paragraphs": 
                [
                    {
                        "id": 21.09,
                        "content": "For the second person singular, the negative is formed with the infinitive of the verb preceded by non. For the other persons, the usual rule applies and non precedes the form of the imperative. As an example, here is the negative conjugation of parlare:",                        "table":{
                            "rows":[
                                ["(tu)", "non parlare"],
                                ["(Lei)", "non parli"],
                                ["(noi)", "non parliamo"],
                                ["(voi)", "non parlate"],
                                ["(Loro)", "non parlino"]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "content": "Examples:",
                        "table":{
                            "rows":[
                                ["Non essere scortese!", "Don’t be rude!"],
                                ["Non dite bugie.", "Don’t tell lies."],
                                ["Non avere fretta!", "Don’t rush"]
                            ]
                        }
                    }
                ]
            },
            {
                "title": "Position of unstressed pronouns",
                "paragraphs": [
                    {
                        "id": 21.10,
                        "content": "When the imperative is used in an affirmative sentence with an unstressed pronoun (direct object, indirect object, reflexive, ne, ci), the pronoun is always attached to the verb if it is in a second person form (tu or voi) or the first person plural form (noi):",
                        "table": {
                            "rows": [
                                ["Quel libro è per te: **prendilo**.", "That book is for you: take it."],
                                ["**Chiediamole** aiuto.", "Let’s ask her for help."],
                                ["Se hai dei problemi, **parlane**.", "If you are having problems, talk about them."],
                                ["**Alzatevi**, ragazzi!", "Get up, boys!"],
                                ["**Telefonagli** (or **Telefona loro** – see Unit 10, paragraph 2).", "Phone them."]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "content": "Note that when an unstressed pronoun is used with the forms **da’**, **fa’**, **di’**, **sta’**, and **va’**, the first consonant of the pronoun (except **gli**) is doubled:",
                        "table": {
                            "rows": [
                                ["Se sai la verità, **dilla**!", "If you know the truth, tell it!"],
                                ["**Dammi** la penna!", "Give me the pen!"],
                                ["**Danne** un po’ a tuo fratello.", "Give some to your brother."],
                                ["**Fammi** un piacere.", "Do me a favour."],
                                ["**Vallo** a comprare!", "Go and buy it!"],
                                ["**Vacci** subito.", "Go there at once."],
                                ["**Dille** la verità.", "Tell her the truth."],
                                ["**Digli** la verità.", "Tell him the truth."]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "content": "In negative sentences, there is an extra option: the pronoun can be placed before the verb (and after **non**):",
                        "table": {
                            "rows": [
                                ["**Non lo prendere**! or **Non prenderlo**!", "Don’t take it!"],
                                ["**Non le chiediamo** aiuto. or **Non chiediamole** aiuto.", "Let’s not ask her for help."],
                                ["**Non ne parlare**! or **Non parlarne**!", "Don’t talk about it!"],
                                ["**Non vi alzate**! or **Non alzatevi**!", "Don’t get up!"]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "id": 21.11,
                        "content": "In the polite form (third person singular and plural, **Lei** and **Loro**), the pronouns are always placed before the verb**:",
                        "table": {
                            "rows": [
                                ["Quel libro è per Lei: **lo prenda**.", "That book is for you: take it."],
                                ["**Le scriva** una mail.", "Write her an email."],
                                ["**Ne parlino** al controllore.", "Speak to the conductor about it."],
                                ["**Si alzi**, Signora!", "Get up, Madam!"]
                            ]
                        }
                    }
                ]
            }
        ]
    },
    "exercises": [
